-- ============================================================
-- Pinecone — single-tool seed (Phase 7 / pre-flight unblock)
-- Pinecone is the load-bearing managed vector DB for the AI dev
-- stack. Required in catalog for the affiliate pre-flight gate
-- (PartnerStack — Pinecone) and as the canonical reference point
-- for every RAG / semantic-search comparison page going forward.
--
-- Editorial parity matches Batch 26 (037 depth fields populated):
-- description, editorial_verdict, best_for, not_for, our_views,
-- limitations, models, use_cases, tutorial_urls, last_verified_at.
-- All website_url / pricing_details verified via WebFetch on
-- pinecone.io and pinecone.io/pricing on 2026-05-01.
--
-- Schema enums (001_initial_schema):
--   pricing_type → 'freemium' (free Starter + paid Standard/Enterprise)
--   skill_level  → 'intermediate'
--   platforms    → {'api','web'}
-- Category link → 'code-development' (vector DB sits in the AI
-- developer-infrastructure slice; same shelf as LangChain et al).
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO tools (
  name, slug, tagline, description, website_url,
  pricing_type, pricing_details, skill_level, has_api, platforms,
  features, integrations, is_published,
  best_for, not_for, editorial_verdict,
  tutorial_urls, limitations, models, community_links, use_cases, our_views,
  last_verified_at
) VALUES
('Pinecone', 'pinecone', 'The purpose-built serverless vector database for production-grade RAG, semantic search, and AI agents.', 'Pinecone is a fully managed, serverless vector database — the storage layer that turns embeddings into a queryable index optimised for similarity search at production scale. The product''s 2024–2025 arc rewrote its own positioning: where Pinecone began as a pod-based managed service (you provisioned p1/s1/p2 capacity and paid for it whether you used it or not), the serverless architecture that went GA in 2024 collapsed that into pure pay-as-you-go on storage, write units, and read units. That single shift is why Pinecone is the default pick for most 2026 RAG stacks rather than just the safe enterprise pick.

The core value is operational. Pinecone removes the work of running a vector index — sharding across regions, real-time upserts without rebuild, namespace-level multi-tenancy, hybrid search that combines BM25-style sparse vectors with dense embeddings in one query, integrated rerankers, and metadata filtering pushed down into the index so you do not have to post-filter results in your app. The platform also hosts embedding models and rerankers (their own and third-party) so a minimal RAG pipeline can be built without leaving the Pinecone API.

Pinecone competes with Weaviate (open-source-first, hybrid-search-native), Qdrant (Rust-based, strong self-host story), Milvus / Zilliz Cloud (the enterprise-Milvus play), Chroma (developer-ergonomic, smaller scale), and pgvector (Postgres extension — the right answer when your data already lives in Postgres and fits comfortably in memory). The differentiation versus that field is rarely raw recall — open-source vector indexes have caught up — but the serverless economics, the maturity of the managed control plane, and the integrations surface (LangChain, LlamaIndex, OpenAI, Cohere, Anthropic, Bedrock, Vertex AI, the Pinecone Assistant API).

For 2026 buyers: Pinecone is the option you reach for when the vector database is load-bearing infrastructure, not a prototype. Production RAG, agent memory, semantic recommendations, and search-relevance pipelines at customers like Gong, Vanguard, and Inkeep all run on this shape of system.', 'https://www.pinecone.io', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Starter","price":"Free","features":["Serverless on-demand database","Up to 2 GB storage","Up to 2M write units / month","Up to 1M read units / month","Community Discord support","Console metrics","On-demand database access"]},{"plan":"Standard","price":"$50/mo minimum + usage","features":["3-week trial includes $300 credits","Storage $0.33/GB/month, unlimited","Writes $4–$4.50 per million (cloud/region dependent)","Reads $16–$18 per million (cloud/region dependent)","Dedicated read nodes","Multiple projects and users","SAML SSO","Role-based access control","Backup and restore","Prometheus metrics export"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"$500/mo minimum + usage","features":["Storage $0.33/GB/month, unlimited","Writes $6–$6.75 per million","Reads $24–$27 per million","99.95% uptime SLA","Private networking","Customer-managed encryption keys (CMEK)","Audit logs","Service accounts and admin APIs","HIPAA compliance included","Dedicated support"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"api","web"}', '{"Managed serverless vector database (no pod sizing)","Hybrid search — sparse (BM25) + dense vectors in one query","Integrated rerankers for precision refinement","Hosted embedding models (Pinecone Inference)","Metadata filtering pushed into the index","Real-time upserts without index rebuild","Namespaces for multi-tenant data partitioning","Sub-100 ms query latency at scale","Pinecone Assistant API for high-level RAG primitives","Backup, restore, and point-in-time recovery (Standard+)","SAML SSO, RBAC, audit logs, CMEK (paid tiers)","Region selection across AWS / GCP / Azure"}', '{"LangChain","LlamaIndex","OpenAI","Anthropic","Cohere","AWS Bedrock","Google Vertex AI","Azure OpenAI","Hugging Face","Haystack","Vercel AI SDK","Datadog","Snowflake","Databricks"}', true, '{"Production RAG pipelines where vector storage is load-bearing infrastructure","AI agents that need persistent semantic memory across sessions","Semantic search and recommendation systems at customer-facing scale","Teams that want managed serverless economics rather than self-hosted ops","Regulated industries needing HIPAA, CMEK, audit logs out of the box"}', '{"Prototypes that fit comfortably in memory (FAISS or in-process is fine)","Stacks already on Postgres where pgvector covers the use case","Teams committed to fully self-hosted infra (Qdrant or Weaviate fit better)","Workloads dominated by structured filtering rather than similarity (use a regular DB)","Cost-sensitive read-heavy workloads where read-unit pricing dominates the budget"}', 'The default vector database for AI applications in 2026. If you''re building anything with embeddings, retrieval, or semantic search at production scale, Pinecone removes the infrastructure problem so you can focus on the application layer. Pick it for production-grade RAG, agent memory, or customer-facing semantic search; skip it if your data fits in memory and you can use FAISS or pgvector locally, or if your stack is already on Postgres and pgvector covers the latency budget.', '{"https://docs.pinecone.io/guides/get-started/quickstart","https://docs.pinecone.io/guides/data/upsert-data","https://docs.pinecone.io/guides/search/hybrid-search"}', 'Read-unit pricing dominates cost on read-heavy workloads — a chatty agent that hits the index 20 times per user turn can outrun a $50/mo Standard minimum surprisingly fast; model unit consumption before committing. Migration off Pinecone is non-trivial: the API surface (sparse + dense + namespaces + metadata filtering + Assistant) is wider than most competitors, so apps that go deep on Pinecone-specific features port slower than apps that treat it as a thin index. Latency floor on serverless is excellent at typical scale but cold reads on very-low-traffic indexes can lag the published sub-100 ms numbers — keep a probe warm if you care. Region availability is broad on AWS, narrower on GCP and Azure. HIPAA compliance is Enterprise-tier only; do not assume it on Standard.', '{"text-embedding-3-large","text-embedding-3-small","Cohere embed-multilingual","pinecone-rerank","cohere-rerank","BM25 sparse"}', '{"reddit_threads":[],"discord":"https://www.pinecone.io/community/","docs":"https://docs.pinecone.io"}'::jsonb, '{"Stand up a production RAG pipeline over a private knowledge base in an afternoon — embed, upsert, query.","Add semantic memory to an AI agent so it recalls prior sessions across days or weeks.","Run hybrid search (BM25 + dense) over a product catalog without standing up Elasticsearch.","Power a customer-facing similarity recommender with namespace-per-tenant isolation.","Replace a hand-rolled FAISS deployment when ops cost outgrew the savings."}', 'Sweet spot: a team building production AI features (RAG, search, agents) where the vector index is critical-path and you do not want a database engineer babysitting it. Serverless economics mean you stop paying for idle pods, hybrid search and rerankers ship without a separate Elasticsearch cluster, and the integrations surface (LangChain / LlamaIndex / OpenAI / Bedrock) means most reference architectures already include Pinecone by default.

Failure modes. The biggest one is cost surprise on read-heavy workloads — chatty agents and high-fanout retrieval can rack up read units fast, and the Standard tier''s $50/mo floor stops being relevant once you''re past trivial scale. The second is feature lock-in: Pinecone-specific primitives (Assistant API, hosted reranker, namespace patterns) are great until you need to migrate, at which point a thin LangChain wrapper is the only thing that saves you. The third is fit: if your data is small enough to live in memory or already lives in Postgres with pgvector, you''re paying for managed infrastructure you do not actually need.

What to pilot. Pick one production-shaped workload — not a hello-world demo. Embed a real corpus (≥100k chunks), turn on hybrid search, add a reranker, run your real query distribution for a week. Measure (a) recall@k against your existing baseline, (b) p95 latency under realistic concurrency, (c) total monthly cost extrapolated from week-one read/write units. If recall is at least as good as your baseline, latency is comfortably under your budget, and projected cost is acceptable, Pinecone is the right call. If any one of those misses, re-evaluate against pgvector (cheaper, simpler) or self-hosted Qdrant / Weaviate (full control, real ops cost).', now())
ON CONFLICT (slug) DO NOTHING;

